"**Comparison of Sajith Premadasa and Ranil Wickremesinghe's Policies**\n\n| **Policy Area** | **Sajith Premadasa** | **Ranil Wickremesinghe** |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 1. Economic Policy and Growth Strategies | Emphasizes building a resilient economy through transparency, accountability, and managing the debt crisis | Aims to establish the Theravada Trade Economy, create 100,000 new employment opportunities, and increase income generation opportunities |\n| 2. Education Reform and Innovation | Prioritizes human capital development, provides free public transportation to teachers, and addresses salary and pension issues | Focuses on modernizing school infrastructure, equipping teachers with new knowledge and training, and encouraging innovation and startups |\n| 3. Energy and Sustainability | Aims to promote renewable energy, exceed the target of 70% renewable energy generation by 2030, and pursue green hydrogen production | Targets 70% of the power supply network from renewable energy sources by 2030, encourages investments in renewable energy, and establishes a Green Energy Hub |\n| 4. Healthcare System and Public Health | Ensures access to quality healthcare, reinforces the healthcare sector, and implements the National Nutrition Policy | Establishes private hospitals in all nine provinces, introduces a healthcare insurance scheme, and upgrades healthcare services to a higher standard |\n| 5. National Security and Defense | Strengthens national security through defense cooperation, modernizes the armed forces, and provides essential technical facilities and equipment | Enhances the status of the Tri Forces, introduces a One Rank - One Pension system, and encourages the establishment of related manufacturing industries |\n| 6. Legal Framework and Judicial Reform | Enacts legal reforms to prevent executive interference, establishes the independence and efficiency of the judiciary, and creates a strong foundation of rule of law | Introduces a new Constitution, establishes a Parliamentary Standards Act, and reforms the election system |\n| 7. Transportation and Mobility | Builds a multi-faceted public transport system, reallocates economic infrastructure expenditure, and improves the dilapidated rural road network | Provides sustainable green transport services, uses digital technologies for issuing driving licenses, and encourages the use of electrical vehicles |\n| 8. Infrastructure Development and Modernization | Emphasizes building a resilient economy through infrastructure development, improves critical infrastructure, and reallocates economic infrastructure expenditure | Upgrades tourism infrastructure, modernizes school infrastructure, establishes a National Wealth Fund, and restructures the cooperative movement |\n| 9. Foreign Policy and International Relations | Proposes a multi-aligned foreign policy, promotes economic diplomacy, and develops a trade and investment policy | Strengthens institutions, recovers stolen assets, collaborates with international partners, and encourages foreign investment and exports |\n\n**Common Policies:**\n\n* Emphasis on renewable energy and sustainability\n* Focus on improving the healthcare system and providing access to quality healthcare\n* Importance of national security and defense\n* Need for judicial reform and strengthening the legal framework\n\n**Unique/Innovative Policies:**\n\n* Sajith Premadasa:\n\t+ Providing free public transportation to teachers\n\t+ Pursuing green hydrogen production\n\t+ Implementing the National Nutrition Policy\n* Ranil Wickremesinghe:\n\t+ Establishing a Green Energy Hub\n\t+ Introducing a One Rank - One Pension system for the Tri Forces\n\t+ Creating a National Wealth Fund\n\n**Analysis:**\n\n* Sajith Premadasa's policies focus on building a resilient economy, prioritizing human capital development, and promoting renewable energy and sustainability. His manifesto emphasizes the importance of transparency, accountability, and managing the debt crisis.\n* Ranil Wickremesinghe's policies aim to establish the Theravada Trade Economy, create employment opportunities, and increase income generation opportunities. His manifesto focuses on modernizing school infrastructure, equipping teachers with new knowledge and training, and encouraging innovation and startups.\n* Both candidates prioritize national security and defense, judicial reform, and foreign policy, but their approaches differ in some areas."